        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We need to obtain the broad line from AGN, which have the line width of several thousands of km/s. So the velocity resolution is not too important for our observaion, while we need wide bandwidth to cover the broad line.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Since we only need the spectral information, any angular resolution of ALMA is OK for this project.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The RRL that we propose to observe will have the line width (FWHM) of about 3300 km/s. So we do not need very high frequency resolution for this observation. With 100 km/s velocity resolution, we can obtain the rms level of 0.15mJy (4mK of brightness temperature for 1.5 arcsecond beam) with 2 hour observing time (about1.18 hours on source) at 5th Octile weather condition using dual polarization data. Detailed estimation of expected emission was presented in the Technical consideration part of the pdf file.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
